Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

> Uploaded patch set 3.

I fixed a call to test_utils.start_http_server() in test_api: the image data must be a bytes string, otherwise we get an eventlet failure.

I still get random failures when I run "tox -e py34". I suggest to *NOT MERGE* this change until we identified and fixed the random failures. So I vote -1 on our patch :-)

Patch Set 3:

See also my change I0d434b04db78b2319b723e5968effdde766368c9 which fix an Unicode issue on Python 3 which is not seen by running unit tests.

I found the issue by running tests with "python3 -bb" to get BytesWarning. But to run these tests, I had to issues bytes vs text issues in pep8, oslo.context and routes :-/

* routes: https://github.com/bbangert/routes/pull/56
* pep8: https://github.com/PyCQA/pep8/pull/459
* oslo.context: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/250736/

Patch Set 4:

The change Ib342ef6640efbc3d76c4bafc622ccfdfa3d16ade was merged before this change and it added new tests to test_api which fail on Python 3. I wrote a fix for it: change Id1dbf98ecf23e401f696a575dfea80fac2e297ed. So I based this change on the fix.

I still get some random failures on glance.tests.unit.v1.test_api.TestGlanceAPI.test_create_image_with_nonexistent_location_url because it's really hard to reproduce the issue. It looks like the failure only occurs when the tests are run with "tox -e py34". If I only run the failing test alone with testtools.run: it pass. If I run test_api: it pass. If I run the whole test suite with tox: it fails randomly.

Workaround(?): It looks like the test doesn't fail anymore if I added --no-parallel to the "python setup.py testr ..." command for py34 in tox.ini.

Patch Set 4:

So, if there really is just *one* test failing, I'd be ok with skipping it on Python 3 and opening a bug report. That would allow us to have all the unit tests running, except for this one, and would probably help catch most new regressions.

WDYT?

Patch Set 4:

Cyril: "So, if there really is just *one* test failing, (...)"

Well, not exactly. The full test suite just succeeded, Jenkins is happy.

But yeah, if a test becomes unstable, we can skip it and then try to investigate why it fails randomly.
